🔍 𝐐𝐓𝐑-𝟏𝟔 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐬𝐨𝐫 𝐓𝐞𝐬𝐭 (𝐒𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐥 𝐎𝐮𝐭𝐩𝐮𝐭)

This project is a standalone test utility for the 16-element analog QTR sensor array, designed to verify sensor functionality and calibration by printing readings directly to the Serial Monitor.

It helps you debug wiring, check sensor health, and visualize line detection values before integrating into a PID line follower.

⚙️ Hardware Used:
  📡 Sensor Array: Pololu QTR-16 Analog Sensor Array
  🧩 Microcontroller: Teensy 4.1 (or any compatible board with enough ADC pins)
🧠 What This Code Does:
  Initializes all 16 analog sensors
  Performs automatic calibration
  Reads:
    📍 Line position value
    📊 Raw sensor readings
  Prints everything to the Serial Monitor for analysis

🔌 Pin Configuration:

The sensors are connected to the following ADC-capable pins:

const uint8_t sensors[16] = {
  14, 15, 16, 17,
  20, 21, 22, 23,
  24, 25, 26, 27,
  38, 39, 40, 41
};

⚠️ Make sure:

All pins support analog input (ADC)
Wiring matches your microcontroller

🔄 Calibration Process

At startup, the system performs calibration:

for (int i = 0; i < 200; i++) {
  qtr.calibrate();
  delay(20);
}
✅ Important:
Move the sensor over both black line and white surface
Ensure full coverage for accurate calibration

📟 Serial Output
Open Serial Monitor at:
Baud Rate: 115200

You will see output like:

Position: 7423 | Sensors: 1023 980 850 ... 120
📌 Meaning:
Position (0 → ~15000)
Indicates where the line is relative to the sensor array

Sensor Values
Higher values → stronger reflection (depends on surface & calibration)
🚀 How to Use:
  Upload the code to your microcontroller
  Open Serial Monitor (115200 baud)
  Move the sensor over the track
  Observe:
    Position shifting left/right
    Sensor values changing across the array
